[[File:IiroViinanenPaasitorniPoliittisenHistorianKlubi2015 DSCN4210 (5).JPG|thumb|250px|Iiro Viinanen (2015)]] '''Iiro Viinanen''' (born September 27, 1944, [[Kuopio]], [[Finland]]) is a [[Finland|Finnish]] politician. Viinanen graduated as an engineer from a Tampere institute in 1967 and as a [[Diplomi-insinööri|M.Sc. Tech.]] from [[Helsinki University of Technology]] in 1974 . He was a Member of the [[Parliament of Finland|Finnish Parliament (Eduskunta / Riksdagen)]] from 1983 to 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.eduskunta.fi/triphome/bin/hx5000.sh?{hnro}=293&{kieli}=su&{haku}=kaikki |title=Edustajamatrikkeli |publisher=Eduskunta}}</ref> His political party was [[National Coalition Party (Finland)|National Coalition Party]]. He served as the [[Minister of Finance (Finland)|Minister of Finance]] from 1991 to 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://valtioneuvosto.fi/tietoa/historiaa/hallitukset-ja-ministerit/raportti/-/r/v9l/13 |title=Council of State - Ministers of Finance|publisher=Valtioneuvosto.fi |accessdate=12 January 2018 |deadurl=no }}</ref>
During his term as a minister, Finland went through its worst recession in history. As the Minister of Finance in [[Prime Minister of Finland|Prime Minister]] [[Esko Aho's cabinet]] he led strict budget discipline. He stated that unless budget is cut, Finland can no longer borrow money from foreign countries. Reactions towards his actions caused either strong approval or strong disapproval. Some felt he saved the treasury and some felt he ruined the Finnish welfare state.
In 1996 he was appointed CEO of [[OP Financial Group|Pohjola Insurance]]. At the end of the 1990s he was a board member of [[Nokia]], [[Kone]], [[UPM-Kymmene]], [[YIT]], [[Finnair]], and [[Orion corporation|Orion]]. He served as a vice chairman of Nokia from 1996 to 2000.
He was diagnosed with [[Parkinson's disease]] in 2000, forcing him to retire.
