'''María de Lourdes''' "'''Mia'''" '''Villiers Farrow''' ({{IPAc-en|'|m|ɑː|r|iː|ɑː|_|d|i|_|l|ʊ|r|d|z|_|v|ɪ|l|j|ə|r|z|_|f|æ|r|oʊ}}; born February 9, 1945) is an American actress, activist, and former fashion model. Farrow has appeared in more than 50 films and won numerous awards, including a [[Golden Globe Award]] and three [[BAFTA Award]] nominations. Farrow is also known for her extensive work as a [[List of UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors|UNICEF Goodwill Ambassador]], which includes humanitarian activities in [[Darfur]], [[Chad]], and the [[Central African Republic]]. In 2008, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine named her one of the most influential people in the world.<ref>{{cite news|author1=[[Paul Rusesabagina|Rusesabagina, Paul]]|title=Heroes & Pioneers: Mia Farrow|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1733748_1733756_1735264,00.html|accessdate=October 6, 2014|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|publisher=Time Inc|date=May 12, 2008}}</ref>

The daughter of Australian director [[John Farrow]] and Irish actress [[Maureen O'Sullivan]], Farrow had a strict [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] upbringing in [[Beverly Hills, California]]. After working as a fashion model during her teenage years, she first gained notice for her role as [[Allison MacKenzie]] in the television [[soap opera]] ''[[Peyton Place (TV series)|Peyton Place]]'' and gained further recognition for her subsequent short-lived marriage to [[Frank Sinatra]], whom she married at age 22. An early film role, as Rosemary in [[Roman Polanski]]'s ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]'' (1968), saw her nominated for a [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|BAFTA Award]] and a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress – Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe Award for Best Actress]]. She went on to appear in several films throughout the 1970s, such as ''[[Follow Me! (1972 film)|Follow Me!]]'' (1972), ''[[The Great Gatsby (1974 film)|The Great Gatsby]]'' (1974), and ''[[Death on the Nile (1978 film)|Death on the Nile]]'' (1978). 

Farrow was in a relationship with actor-director [[Woody Allen]] from 1980 to 1992 and appeared in thirteen of his fourteen films over that period, including ''[[Zelig]]'' (1983), ''[[Broadway Danny Rose]]'' (1984), ''[[The Purple Rose of Cairo]]'' (1985), ''[[Hannah and Her Sisters]]'' (1986), ''[[Radio Days]]'' (1987), ''[[Crimes and Misdemeanors]]'' (1989), ''[[Alice (1990 film)|Alice]]'' (1990), and ''[[Husbands and Wives]]'' (1992). Her later film roles include ''[[Widows' Peak]]'' (1994), ''[[The Omen (2006 film)|The Omen]]'' (2006), ''[[Be Kind Rewind]]'' (2008), ''[[Dark Horse (2011 film)|Dark Horse]]'' (2011), and [[Luc Besson]]'s [[Arthur series (Besson)|''Arthur'' series]] (2006–2010).

==Early life==
[[File:John Farrow family 1950.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1|Farrow (far left) with her family, 1950]]
María de Lourdes Villiers Farrow<ref name=lax/> was born February 9, 1945{{sfn|Bartrop|2012|p=86}} in [[Los Angeles]], California, the third child and eldest daughter of Australian film director [[John Farrow]] and Irish actress [[Maureen O'Sullivan]]. Her father converted to her mother's Catholic religion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/weta/finding-your-roots/blog/mia-farrows-interactive-family-tree/|work=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] (OPB)|publisher=[[PBS]]|location=Portland, Oregon|title=Mia Farrow’s Interactive Family Tree|date=March 9, 2016|accessdate=December 28, 2016}}</ref> She is one of seven children, with older brothers Michael Damien (1939–1958), [[Patrick Villiers Farrow|Patrick]] (1942–2009),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://patrickfarrow.com/biography.html|work=Patrick Villiers Farrow|title=Patrick Villiers Farrow, Sculptor|accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref> younger brother John Charles (born 1946); and younger sisters [[Prudence Farrow|Prudence]] and actresses Stephanie and [[Tisa Farrow|Tisa]].{{Sfn|Current Biography Yearbook|1970|p=132}}

Her eldest brother, Michael Farrow, died in a plane crash in 1958, at age 19;<ref name=legos/> Patrick, a sculptor, committed suicide in 2009;<ref>{{cite news|title=Mia Farrow's Brother's Death: SUICIDE|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/06/17/mia-farrows-brother-kille_n_216900.html|author=Ring, Wilson|date= June 17, 2009|website=[[The Huffington Post]]}}</ref> and John Charles was convicted of [[child sexual abuse|sexually abusing]] two young boys in 2013 and sentenced to 10 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/Mia-Farrows-Brother-to-Be-Sentenced-for-Sex-Abuse-229522321.html|title=Mia Farrow's Brother Sentenced for Child Sex Abuse|website=[[NBC]]|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|location=New York City|date=October 28, 2013|accessdate=October 12, 2018}}</ref> Her sister Prudence inspired [[John Lennon]] to write the song "[[Dear Prudence]]".<ref>{{cite magazine|first=David|last=Chiu|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-real-dear-prudence-on-meeting-beatles-in-india-74048/|title=The Real ‘Dear Prudence’ on Meeting Beatles in India|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Wenner Media LLC|location=New York City|date=September 4, 2015|accessdate=October 12, 2018}}</ref>

Farrow grew up primarily in [[Beverly Hills, California]], where she occasionally put on performances with "toy daggers and fake blood" for passing celebrity tour buses.<ref name=grauniad/> Aged two, she made her film debut in a short documentary, ''Unusual Occupations: Film Tot Holiday'' (1947).{{Sfn|Holmes|Negra|2011|p=239}} She was raised as a [[Roman Catholic]], and received her primary and high school education at a Catholic [[convent]] by nuns.<ref name=grauniad>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2006/jan/29/2|title='I've always had a sense of the unworthiness of myself'|publisher= [[Guardian Media Group]]|work=[[The Observer]]|date=January 29, 2006|first=Gaby|last=Wood|location=London, UK}}</ref><ref name=pringle>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/mia-farrow-my-faith-helps-me-through-hard-times-480665.html|title=Mia Farrow: 'My faith helps me through hard times'|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Limited|date=June 2, 2006|first=Gill|last=Pringle|location=London}}</ref> When she was nine, she contracted [[polio]] during an outbreak in Los Angeles reportedly affecting 500 people.<ref>
{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49874251|title=Polio Strikes Los Angeles|newspaper=[[The West Australian]]|location=Perth|date=August 14, 1954|accessdate=March 3, 2012|page=4|publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> She was placed in an isolation ward for three weeks<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/09/26/nyregion/public-lives-older-wiser-and-still-reaching-out-to-help.html|author=Wadler, Joyce|title=PUBLIC LIVES; Older, Wiser and Still Reaching Out to Help|newspaper= | accessdate=August 10, 2013|date=September 26, 2000}}</ref> and later said the experience "marked the end of [her] childhood".<ref name=grauniad/> After the 1959 death of Farrow's brother, Michael, she and her family relocated to [[Surrey]], England; her father began drinking heavily during this period, which caused strain on his marriage to her mother.{{sfn|Farrow|1997|pages=50–51}} He died of a heart attack in Los Angeles four years later, when Farrow was 17 years old.{{sfn|Farrow|1997|p=59}}

==Career==
===1963–1979===
[[File:Mia Farrow 1965 press photo.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Farrow photographed in 1965]]
Before her acting career, Farrow worked as a fashion model for many years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com.au/beauty/vogue+loves/beauty+icon+mia+farrow,14939|author=Hall, Anni| title=Beauty icon: Mia Farrow|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|publisher=[[Condé Nast]]|date=October 25, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111130092742/https://www.vogue.com.au/beauty/vogue+loves/beauty+icon+mia+farrow,14939|archive-date=November 30, 2011}}</ref> She screen-tested for the role of Liesl von Trapp in ''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]'', but did not get the part.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-10912919| title=Profile: Mia Farrow|publisher=BBC News|date=August 9, 2010|accessdate=August 7, 2013}}</ref> The footage has been preserved, and appears on the fortieth Anniversary Edition DVD of ''The Sound of Music''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Von Trapp Family Reunites!|url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=1303227|work=ABC News|date=November 11, 2005}}</ref>  Farrow began her acting career by appearing in supporting roles in several 1960s films, making her first credited appearance in ''[[Guns at Batasi]]'' (1964). The same year, she achieved stardom on the popular [[Prime time|primetime]] soap opera ''[[Peyton Place (TV series)|Peyton Place]]'' as naive, waif-like [[Allison MacKenzie]].<ref name=momma>{{cite web|last=Orth|first=Maureen|title=Momma Mia!|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2013/11/mia-farrow-frank-sinatra-ronan-farrow|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|publisher=[[Condé Nast]]|date=November 2013|accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref> Farrow left the series in 1966 at the urging of [[Frank Sinatra]] whom she married on July 19, 1966.{{Sfn|Newcomb|2004|p=1755}}{{Sfn|Toth|1981|p=357}}

Farrow's first leading film role was in ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]'' (1968), which was a critical and commercial success at the time and continues to be widely regarded as a classic of the horror genre. Her performance garnered numerous awards, including the [[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year – Actress]], and established her as a leading actress. Film critic and author Stephen Farber described her performance as having an "electrifying impact... one of the rare instances of actor and character achieving a miraculous, almost mythical match". Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] called the film "brilliant", and noted, "A great deal of the credit for this achievement must go to Mia Farrow, as Rosemary".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19680729/REVIEWS/807290301/1023|author=Ebert, Roger|work=Chicago Sun-Times|date=July 29, 1968|title=Rosemary's Baby}}</ref>

[[File:Dustin Hoffman and Mia Farrow - John and Mary (1969).jpg|thumb|upright|right|Farrow and [[Dustin Hoffman]] in ''[[John and Mary (film)|John and Mary]]'' (1969)]]
Following ''Rosemary's Baby'', Farrow was to be cast as Mattie in ''[[True Grit (1969 film)|True Grit]]'' and was keen on the role. However, prior to filming she made ''[[Secret Ceremony]]'' in England with [[Elizabeth Taylor]] and [[Robert Mitchum]]. While filming, Mitchum told her about ''True Grit'' director [[Henry Hathaway]] having a reputation for being rude to actresses. Farrow asked producer [[Hal Wallis]] to replace Hathaway. Wallis refused; Farrow then quit the role, which was then given to [[Kim Darby]].<ref>Davis, Ronald L. (2003), ''Duke: The Life and Image of John Wayne'', University of Oklahoma Press, p. 286.</ref> ''Secret Ceremony'' divided critics, but has gone on to develop a devoted following. Farrow's other late 1960s films include ''John and Mary'', opposite [[Dustin Hoffman]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Happy ending for Mia |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1300&dat=19691211&id=u8hUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=z5ADAAAAIBAJ&pg=6494,2092771&hl=sv |newspaper=The Age |publisher=Google News Archive |date=December 11, 1969 |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref>

In the 1970s, Farrow performed in several classical plays in London including ''[[Mary Rose (play)|Mary Rose]]'', ''[[The Three Sisters (play)|The Three Sisters]]'', and ''[[Ivanov (play)|Ivanov]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Farrow, Mia 1945(?)-|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Mia_Farrow.aspx|website=Encyclopedia.com|accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> She became the first American actress to join the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]].{{Sfn|Bartrop|2012|p=86}} During this time she appeared in several films, including the thriller ''[[See No Evil (1971 film)|See No Evil]]'' (1971), French director [[Claude Chabrol]]'s ''Docteur Popaul'' (1972) and ''[[The Great Gatsby (1974 film)|The Great Gatsby]]'' (1974), in which Farrow played Daisy Buchanan. She appeared in director [[Robert Altman]]'s cult classic ''[[A Wedding]]'' (1978). In 1977, she played the title role in ''[[The Haunting of Julia]]''. Farrow appeared in several made-for-television films in the 1970s, most notably portraying the title role in a musical version of ''[[Peter Pan]]'' (1976). In 1979, she appeared on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] opposite [[Anthony Perkins]] in the play ''[[Romantic Comedy (play)|Romantic Comedy]]'' by [[Bernard Slade]].<ref name=romantic/>{{sfn|Farrow|1997|p=170}}

===1980–present===
{{quote box|align=right|width=25em|bgcolor = Cornsilk|quote="She's a good actress, and in my opinion she's actually underrated by Hollywood...So I always felt she didn't get her just acclaim as an actress. I never had any problems with her as an actress, our problems were purely personal. Professionally, she was easy to work with. She was creative. She had good range, she could do broad comedy as well as very serious parts. As a performer I have only good things to say about her, and I always thought she was neglected in terms of her approbation."|source=[[Woody Allen]]{{sfn|Allen|1993|p=271}} }}

[[File:Mia Farrow -1980.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Farrow in 1980]]
In the 1980s and early 1990s, Farrow's relationship with director [[Woody Allen]] resulted in numerous film collaborations. She appeared in nearly all of Allen's films during this period, including leading roles in ''[[Zelig]]'', ''[[Broadway Danny Rose]]'', ''[[The Purple Rose of Cairo]]'', ''[[Hannah and Her Sisters]]'', ''[[Radio Days]]'' and ''[[Alice (1990 film)|Alice]]'' (1990). Farrow played Alura, mother of Kara ([[Helen Slater]]), in ''[[Supergirl (1984 film)|Supergirl]]'' (1984) and voiced the title role in the animated film ''[[The Last Unicorn (film)|The Last Unicorn]]'' (1982). She narrated several of the animated ''[[Stories to Remember]]''. Allen said that the way she played her character in ''Broadway Danny Rose'' was a "very, very brave thing for her to do," as she had to play her role without ever using her eyes.{{sfn|Allen|1993|p=147}}

Citing the need to devote herself to raising her young children, Farrow worked less frequently during the 1990s. Nonetheless, she appeared in leading roles in several films, including the Irish film ''[[Widows' Peak]]'' (1994), ''[[Miami Rhapsody]]'' (1995) and ''[[Reckless (1995 film)|Reckless]]'' (also 1995). She appeared in several independent features and made-for-television films throughout the late 1990s and early 2000s and wrote an autobiography, ''What Falls Away'', in 1997.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/02/23/reviews/970223.23harrist.html| title=Intimate Strangers|author=Harrison, Kathryn|publisher=Books, ''The New York Times''|date=February 23, 1997|accessdate=August 8, 2013}}</ref>

Farrow appeared as Mrs. Baylock, the [[Satanism|Satanic]] nanny, in the remake of ''[[The Omen (2006 film)|The Omen]]'' (2006). Although the film itself received a lukewarm critical reception, Farrow's performance was widely praised, with the [[Associated Press]] declaring "thank heaven for Mia Farrow" and calling her performance "a rare instance of the new ''Omen'' improving on the old one."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://old.chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2006/06/06/mov_84223.shtml|title=At the Movies: 'The Omen'|work=[[The Augusta Chronicle]]|location=Augusta, Georgia|date=June 6, 2006|agency=Associated Press|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028191434/http://old.chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2006/06/06/mov_84223.shtml|archive-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref> Filmcritic.com added "it is Farrow who steals the show,"<ref>[http://filmcritic.com/misc/emporium.nsf/0/fbedd890143aecc48825717a0074e8ef?OpenDocument The Omen (2006) Movie Review, DVD Release] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311134110/http://filmcritic.com/misc/emporium.nsf/0/fbedd890143aecc48825717a0074e8ef?OpenDocument |date=March 11, 2007 }}, Filmcritic.com; accessed October 6, 2014.</ref> and the ''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]'' described her performance as "a truly delicious comeback role for Rosemary herself, Mia Farrow, who is chillingly believable as a sweet-talking nanny from hell."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/movies/272809_omen06q.html|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|first1=William|last1=Arnold|title=Final warning: Don't see 'Omen'|date=May 6, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131229161052/https://www.seattlepi.com/ae/movies/article/Final-warning-Don-t-see-Omen-1205334.php|archive-date=December 29, 2013}}</ref> She worked on several films released in 2007, including the romantic comedy ''[[The Ex (2007 film)|The Ex]]'' and the first part of director [[Luc Besson]]'s trilogy of fantasy films, ''[[Arthur and the Invisibles]].'' In 2008, in director [[Michel Gondry]]'s ''[[Be Kind Rewind]]'', she appeared opposite [[Jack Black]], [[Mos Def]] and [[Danny Glover]]. In 2011, Farrow appeared in the film ''[[Dark Horse (2011 film)|Dark Horse]]'', directed by [[Todd Solondz]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Borys |last=Kit |title=Christopher Walken among cast of Todd Solondz drama |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/christopher-walken-among-cast-todd-29707 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=October 14, 2010 |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Daniel |last=D'Addario |title=Dark Horse by Todd Solondz reviewed: Despite fast start, film falls to back of the pack |url=http://observer.com/2012/06/dark-horse-by-todd-solondz-reviewed-despite-fast-start-film-falls-to-back-of-the-pack/ |work=The New York Observer |date=June 5, 2012 |accessdate=March 6, 2016}}</ref>

In September 2014, Farrow returned to Broadway in the play ''[[Love Letters (play)|Love Letters]]''. The play was well received by critics<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sheward|first1=David|title=Review Roundup: ‘Love Letters’|url=http://www.newyork.com/articles/broadway/review-roundup-love-letters-36626/|accessdate=January 5, 2015|work=NewYork.com|date=19 September 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216155626/http://www.newyork.com/articles/broadway/review-roundup-love-letters-36626/|archivedate=February 16, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> with the ''[[New York Times]]'' calling Farrow's performance "utterly extraordinary… as the flighty, unstable and writing-averse Melissa Gardner."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Isherwood|first1=Charles|title=The Muted Melancholy Between the Lines|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/19/theater/brian-dennehy-and-mia-farrow-in-love-letters-on-broadway.html?_r=1|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 18, 2014}}</ref>

==Humanitarian activities==
[[File:MiaFarrowAfrica.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Farrow during a visit to the [[Central African Republic]]]]
Farrow became a [[UNICEF Goodwill Ambassador]] in 2000 and is a high-profile advocate for [[human rights in Africa]], particularly for children's rights. She has worked to raise funds and awareness for children in conflict-affected regions and to draw attention to the fight to [[Poliomyelitis eradication|eradicate polio]].{{Sfn|Bartrop|2012|p=86}} Farrow has received several awards for her humanitarian work<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refugeesinternational.org/press-room/press-release/release-ri-honor-mia-farrow-and-ronan-farrow-29th-anniversary-dinner|title=McCall-Pierpaoli Humanitarian Award press release|accessdate=August 13, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928122839/http://www.refugeesinternational.org/press-room/press-release/release-ri-honor-mia-farrow-and-ronan-farrow-29th-anniversary-dinner|archivedate=September 28, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unicef.org/people/people_mia_farrow.html|title=Mia Farrow Goodwill Ambassador|publisher=Unicef|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> including the Leon Sullivan International Service award,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bnonews.com/urgent/4941/unicef-ambassador-mia-farrow-to-meet-war-affected-children-in-uganda|title=UNICEF Ambassador Mia Farrow to meet war-affected children in Uganda|accessdate=August 7, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140218223100/http://bnonews.com/urgent/4941/unicef-ambassador-mia-farrow-to-meet-war-affected-children-in-uganda/|archivedate=February 18, 2014|df=mdy-all|work=BNO News}}</ref> the Lyndon Baines Johnson Moral Courage Award<ref>{{cite web|title=Lyndon Baines Johnson Moral Courage Award|url=https://www.hmh.org/au_award_page25.shtml|publisher=Holocaust Museum Houston|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref> and the Marion Anderson Award.<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 Past Honorees Mia Farrow|url=http://www.marianandersonaward.org/#/index.php/past-honorees/mia-farrow/|website=The Marion Anderson Award|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref> In 2006, Farrow and her son Ronan visited [[Berlin]] in order to participate in a charity auction of [[United Buddy Bears]],<ref>[http://www.kennethinthe212.com/2006/07/mia-and-woody.html Mia and Ronan Farrow in Berlin in 2006 (2 photos)]</ref> which feature designs by artists representing 142 U.N. member states.<ref>[http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/6207/1664/1600/mia%20farrow.jpg Mia Farrow and the United Buddy Bears in Berlin 2006]</ref> In 2008, ''Time'' magazine named her one of the most influential people in the world.{{Sfn|Bartrop|2012|pages=86–87}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1733748_1733756_1735264,00.html|title=The 2008 ''Time 100'' Heroes & Pioneers: Mia Farrow|accessdate=August 15, 2013|date=May 12, 2008|first=Paul|last=Rusesabagina}}</ref>

She has traveled to [[Darfur conflict|Darfur]] several times for humanitarian efforts, first in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/mia-farrows-exclusive-dispatch-i-am-a-witness-to-darfurs-suffering-5334926.html|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Limited|title=Mia Farrow's exclusive dispatch: I am a witness to Darfur's suffering|date=August 27, 2007|archive-url=http://archive.is/R1Bql|archive-date=November 7, 2018}}</ref> Her third trip was in 2007, with a film crew engaged in making the documentary ''Darfur: On Our Watch''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frontline: On Our Watch (transcript)|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/darfur/etc/script.html|publisher=[[PBS]]|accessdate=October 6, 2014|date=November 20, 2007}}</ref> The same year, she co-founded the [[Olympic Dream for Darfur]] campaign, which drew attention to China's support for the government of Sudan. The campaign hoped to change China's policy by embarrassing it in the run-up to the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] held in [[Beijing]]. In March 2007, China said it would urge Sudan to engage with the international community. The campaign persuaded [[Steven Spielberg]] to withdraw as an artistic adviser to the opening ceremony. During the Olympics, Farrow televised via the internet from a Sudanese refugee camp to highlight China's involvement in the region.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/30/magazine/30olympics-t.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Changing the Rules of the Games|author=Greenburg, Ilan|work=The New York Times Magazine|date=March 30, 2008|accessdate=August 12, 2013}}</ref>

[[File:Mia Farrow in discussion with EUFOR soldier (2530868572).jpg|thumb|upright=1|right|Farrow speaking to a [[European Union Military Operation in Chad and the Central African Republic|European Union Force Chad]] soldier in Darfur, 2008]]
Later in 2007, Farrow offered to "trade her freedom" for the freedom of a humanitarian worker for the Sudan Liberation Army who was being treated in a UN hospital while under threat of arrest. She wanted to be taken captive in exchange for his being allowed to leave the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1559602/Mia-Farrow-offers-freedom-to-save-Darfur-rebel.html|author=Holt, Richard|title=Mia Farrow offers freedom to save Darfur rebel|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|date=August 7, 2007|location=London|archive-date=October 10, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010113146/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1559602/Mia-Farrow-offers-freedom-to-save-Darfur-rebel.html}}</ref> Farrow is also a board member of the Washington, D.C. based non-profit Darfur Women Action Group (DWAG).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.darfurwomenaction.org/about/board/mia-farrow-member-darfur-women-action-group%E2%80%99s-advisory-board |archivedate=September 10, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910093448/http://www.darfurwomenaction.org/about/board/mia-farrow-member-darfur-women-action-group%E2%80%99s-advisory-board |title=Mia Farrow, Member of Darfur Women Action Group’s Advisory Board |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>

In 2009, Farrow narrated a documentary, ''[[As We Forgive]]'', relating the struggle of many of the survivors of the [[Rwandan Genocide]] to forgive those who murdered family and friends.{{Sfn|Bartrop|2012|p=87}} To show "solidarity with the people of Darfur" Farrow began a water-only [[Fasting|fast]] on April 27, 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sudan-darfur-farrow-idINTRE53K65T20090421|author=Charbonneau, Louis|title=Mia Farrow to start fast over Darfur|agency=Reuters|date=April 22, 2009|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> Farrow's goal was to fast for three weeks, but she called a halt after twelve days on the advice of her doctor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Movies/05/08/mia.farrow.strike/index.html|author=Duke, Alan|title=Mia Farrow ends fast after health concerns|publisher=CNN|date=May 8, 2009|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> In August 2010, she testified in the trial against former [[President of Liberia|Liberian President]] [[Charles Taylor (Liberia)|Charles Taylor]] in the [[Special Court for Sierra Leone]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2010/aug/09/mia-farrow-contradicts-naomi-campbell|title=Mia Farrow contradicts Naomi Campbell in Charles Taylor trial|author=Davies, Lizzy (in The Hague), and Adam Gabbatt|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=August 9, 2010}}</ref>

Farrow helped build The Darfur Archives, which document the cultural traditions of the tribes of [[Darfur]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Sudan and Darfur Research Collections|url=http://sudan.uconn.edu/farrow_darfur_archives.htm|publisher=[[Thomas J. Dodd Research Center]], University of Connecticut|accessdate=January 6, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304125803/http://sudan.uconn.edu/farrow_darfur_archives.htm|archivedate=March 4, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She has filmed some 40 hours of songs, dances, children's stories, farming methods and accounts of genocide in the region's refugee camps that make up the current archives.<ref name=mass>{{cite news|author1=Farrow, Mia  |author2=Goldhagen, Daniel Jonah|title=Mass Slaughter and Obama's Mystifying Indifference|url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424127887324463604579040654002211502|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=September 26, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126132057/https://www.wsj.com/articles/mass-slaughter-and-obama8217s-mystifying-indifference-1380236391?tesla=y|archive-date=November 26, 2017}}</ref> Since 2011 the Archives have been housed at the [[Thomas J. Dodd Research Center]] at the [[University of Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Megan|first1=Kathleen|title=Mia Farrow Documents Darfuri Culture|url=http://articles.courant.com/2011-10-11/news/hc-farrow-archives-uconn-1012-20111011_1_refugee-camp-farrow-darfur-region|accessdate= January 6, 2015|work=[[Hartford Courant|The Hartford Courant]]|location=Hartford, Connecticut|date=October 11, 2011}}</ref> In 2013, Farrow criticized President [[Barack Obama]] for his lack of address regarding [[War in Darfur|Sudanese genocide]] during a [[United Nations General Assembly]].<ref name=mass/> In February 2015, Farrow appeared in an episode of ''A Path Appears'', a [[PBS]] documentary series from the creators of the [[Half the Sky movement]]. In the episode Farrow travels to [[Kibera]], [[Kenya]]’s largest slum, to share stories from organizations providing education to at-risk girls.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Locker|first1=Melissa|title=A Path Appears: can celebrities really help tackle humanity's biggest problems?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/feb/02/a-path-appears-pbs-documentary-charities-eva-longoria|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=February 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Carmen|first1=Allison|title=Ronan and Mia Farrow Find Shining Hope in One of the World's Worst Slums|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/allison-carmen/ronan-and-mia-farrow-find_b_6627410.html|accessdate=  February 23, 2015|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|publisher=[[Oath Inc.]]|date= February 6, 2015}}</ref>

Farrow has also participated in environmental activism, in 2014 protesting against [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]], accusing the oil company of environmental damage in the South American rainforest.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/business/21598641-judge-finds-foul-play-behind-controversial-case-against-chevron-courtroom-drama|title=Judge finds foul play behind controversial case against Chevron|work=[[The Economist]]|date=March 8, 2014}}</ref>

==Personal life==
===Religious and political beliefs===
In February 1968, Farrow traveled to India, where she spent part of the year at the [[ashram]] of [[Maharishi Mahesh Yogi]] in [[Rishikesh]], [[Uttarakhand]], studying [[Transcendental Meditation]].{{Sfn|Kaiser|2012|p=212}} Her visit received worldwide media attention because of [[The Beatles at Rishikesh|the presence]] of all four members of [[The Beatles]], [[Donovan]], and [[Mike Love]], as well as her sister Prudence Farrow.{{Sfn|Warner|2004|p=52}}{{Sfn|Lee|1999|p=89}} 

While she has been critical of the [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic Church]] (notably in the Pope's failure to intervene in the [[Rwandan genocide|genocide in Rwanda]], a predominantly Catholic country), Farrow is a devout Catholic<ref name=pringle/> and maintained in a 2013 interview with [[Piers Morgan]] that she had not "lost her faith in God".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1303/14/pmt.01.html|work=CNN|title=Interview with Mia Farrow, Martin Sheen and Craig Kielburger; Steubenville, Ohio Rape Case Shining Light on Rape of Young Girls in America (Transcript)|date=March 14, 2013|accessdate=April 17, 2017|people=Farrow, Mia; [[Martin Sheen]] and [[Piers Morgan]]}}</ref> 

Farrow has stated that she has long been a registered [[Independent Party (United States)|Independent]], though she has consistently voted for [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidates.<ref name=cbsn>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CNCivk5g9Kc|title=Mia Farrow on her Democratic voice|date=April 26, 2016|work=[[CBSN]]|publisher=[[CBS News]]}}</ref> In the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 Democratic presidential election]], Farrow endorsed [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]] candidate [[Bernie Sanders]],<ref>{{cite web|first1=Summer|last1=Fields|first2=Louise|last2=Simpson|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/meet-bernie-sanders-top-celebrity-backers/story?id=33020601|title= Meet Bernie Sanders' Top Celebrity Backers|publisher=ABC News|date=August 11, 2015|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Bill|last=Whalen|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/billwhalen/2015/09/11/is-socialism-here-to-stay-or-is-sanders-just-another-dean/#792c7c1449d4|title=Is Socialism Here To Stay In 2016, Or Is Bernie Sanders Just Another Howard Dean?
|work=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]|date=September 11, 2015|accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> though she subsequently stated that "as a pragmatist" she planned to vote for [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref name=cbsn/>

===Relationships and family===
[[File:Mia Farrow and Andre Previn.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Farrow with [[André Previn]], 1971]]
On July 19, 1966, when Farrow was 22 years old,<ref name=legos>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=http://movies2.nytimes.com/books/97/02/23/reviews/farrow-feature.html|title=Picking Up The Legos And The Pieces|last=Smith|first=Dinitia|date=May 8, 1994}}</ref> she married singer [[Frank Sinatra]] at the [[Las Vegas]] home of [[Jack Entratter]].{{Sfn|Ringgold|1989|p=19}}<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/24/fashion/setting-the-record-and-the-hair-straight-mia-farrow-weighs-in-on-her-60s-pixie.html?_r=0| author=Farrow, Mia|title=Setting the Record (and the Hair) Straight| newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 23, 2013|accessdate=August 7, 2013}}</ref> Farrow was 21 years old, Sinatra 50.<ref name=momma/> Sinatra wanted Farrow to give up her acting career, which she initially agreed to do.{{Sfn|Ringgold|1989|p=19}} She accompanied Sinatra while he was shooting several films, but soon tired of doing nothing and signed on to star in ''Rosemary's Baby''. Filming of ''Rosemary's Baby'' ran over its initial schedule, which angered Sinatra, who had cast Farrow in a role in his film ''[[The Detective (1968 film)|The Detective]]''. After Farrow failed to report for filming, Sinatra cast actress [[Jacqueline Bisset]] in Farrow's role.{{Sfn|Ringgold|1989|p= 21}} In November 1967, while Farrow was filming ''Rosemary's Baby'', Sinatra's lawyer served her with divorce papers.{{Sfn|Santopietro|2009|pages=397–398}} Their divorce was finalized in August 1968.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mia Farrow, André Previn Expecting Baby|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1915&dat=19591014&id=kgAhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=2nUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1112,2346143|newspaper=The Day|date=October 14, 1969|page=21}}</ref> Farrow later blamed the demise of the marriage on their age difference, and said she was an "impossibly immature teenager" when she married Sinatra.{{Sfn|Santopietro|2009|p=398}}{{Sfn|Frayn Turner|2004|p=150}} The two remained friends until Sinatra's death.{{Sfn|Santopietro|2009|pages=397–398}}

On September 10, 1970, Farrow married conductor and composer [[André Previn]] in London; she was 25 and he was 41.<ref name=previnmarriage>{{cite news|title=Actress, conductor wed|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1310&dat=19700911&id=OLRVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VOEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5166,2134479|newspaper=[[The Register-Guard]]|location=Eugene, Oregon|date=September 11, 1970|p=3A}}</ref> Farrow had begun a relationship with Previn while he was still married to his second wife, songwriter [[Dory Previn]]. When Farrow became pregnant, Previn left Dory and filed for divorce. Farrow gave birth to twin sons in February 1970,<ref name=previnmarriage/> and Previn's divorce from Dory became final in July 1970.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/artists/dory-previn/biography/|title=About Dory Previn|work=[[MTV]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203184302/http://www.mtv.com/artists/dory-previn/biography/|archive-date=February 3, 2014}}</ref> Dory Previn later wrote a scathing song, titled "Beware of Young Girls", about the loss of her husband to Farrow.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-dory-previn-20120216,0,2450227.story?page=1|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=Valerie J.|last=Nelson|title=Dory Previn dies at 86; Oscar-nominated songwriter|date=February 16, 2012}}</ref> Previn and Farrow divorced in 1979.<ref name=bbc/>

In 1979, Farrow began a relationship with film director [[Woody Allen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Woody Allen|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20109512,00.html|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=December 28, 1992|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222060607/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20109512,00.html|archivedate=February 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=gilatto>{{cite journal|last=Gliatto|first=Tom|title=A Family Affair|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|date=August 31, 1992|volume=38|issue=9|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20108514,00.html|issn=0093-7673}}</ref> During their relationship, Farrow starred in some of Allen's films, and several of her relatives also made appearances.<ref name=gilatto/> Their relationship ended in 1992 when Allen began having an intimate relationship with [[Soon-Yi Previn]] (Farrow's adopted daughter) who was 22 years old at the time.<ref>{{cite web|first=Maureen|last=Orth|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/1992/11/farrow199211|title=Mia’s Story|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|publisher=[[Condé Nast]]|date=November 1992|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref>

