'''Omar Badsha''' is a South African [[documentary photography|documentary photographer]], artist, political and trade union activist and an historian.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutearts.com/artsnews/2002/10/04/30350.html|title=Narratives: Ritual and Graven Images by Omar Badsha|date=5 October 2002|publisher=Absolutearts.com|accessdate=1 August 2010}}</ref> He has exhibited his art in South Africa and internationally. In 2015 he won the Arts & Culture Trust (ACT) Lifetime Achievement Award for Visual Art.<ref name="Award for visual art">{{cite web | url=http://www.artlink.co.za/news_article.htm?contentID=39058 | title=Omar Badsha - Award for Visual Art | publisher=artlink.co.za | date=3 November 2015 | accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref>

==Early life==
Badsha was born in [[Durban]], [[KwaZulu-Natal]] on 27 June 1945. He is a third generation South African of Indian origin and comes from a [[Gujarati Muslims|Gujarati Muslim]] [[Sunni Vohra]] family. His father Ebrahim Badsha was one of the South African pioneer black artists and a founding member of ''Bantu, Indian, Coloured Arts'' (BICA) organisation started by Durban artists in 1951.<ref name="Award for visual art"/>

==Contributions==
In the early 1960s, Badsha produced "resistance art" and won a number of awards including Sir [[Basil Schonland]] prize in 1965 and the Oppenheimer award in 1969 after his work was featured in the Johannesburg exhibition ''Artists of Fame and Promise''.<ref name="changing focus">{{cite web | url=http://mg.co.za/article/2015-06-04-how-omar-badsha-changed-the-photographic-landscape | title=Changing focus: The art and activism of Omar Badsha | publisher=Mail & Guardian Online | date=5 June 2015 | accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref> He became an [[apartheid|anti-apartheid]] activist during his high schools days. He was one of the activists who revived the [[Natal Indian Congress]] in the 1970s and the independent left wing trade union movement that grew out of the famous 1973 Durban strikes. Badsha established and was the first secretary of the ''Chemical Workers Industrial Union''.<ref name="changing focus"/> During this time he was detained and harassed.<ref>{{cite book | title=The Hidden History of South Africa's Book and Reading Cultures | publisher=University of Toronto Press | author=Dick, Archie L. | year=2013 | isbn=9781442695085}}</ref> He was denied a passport and never allowed to travel outside the country until 1990.<ref>{{cite book | title=Congressional Serial Set | publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office | year=1990 | pages=158}}</ref>

In 1982 Badsha cofounded the multiracial organization [[Afrapix]].<ref>{{cite book | title=The Public Sphere From Outside the West | publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing | author=Divya Dwivedi, Sanil V | year=2015 | isbn=9781472571922}}</ref> They took photojournalistic photographs of  effects and impact of apartheid with the aim to create a picture library and "stimulate documentary photography".<ref>{{cite book | title=Art and the End of Apartheid, Volume 2 | publisher=U of Minnesota Press | author=Peffer, John | year=2009 | pages=254 | isbn=9780816650019}}</ref> He is also the founder of [[South African History Project|South African History Online]], South Africa's largest history website.<ref name="Award for visual art"/>

He is the author of a number of photographic books. His first book was ''A Letter to Farzanah'', was banned immediately after its publication in 1979.<ref name="Award for visual art"/>

