{{about|a CIA employee and author|the Argentinian footballer|Víctor Marchetti}}
'''Victor Leo Marchetti, Jr.''' (December 23, 1929-October 19, 2018)<ref>{{Cite news | first = Matt | last = Schudel | author-link = | author = | author2 = | title = Victor Marchetti, disillusioned CIA officer who challenged secrecy rules, dies at 88 | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/victor-marchetti-disillusioned-cia-officer-who-challenged-secrecy-rules-dies-at-88/2018/10/27/a33b1524-d947-11e8-a10f-b51546b10756_story.html | format = | work = | publisher = The Washington Post | pages = | page = | date = 2018-10-27 | access-date = }}</ref> was a special assistant to the [[Deputy Director of the Central Intelligence Agency|Deputy Director]] of the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] who later became a prominent [[paleoconservative]] critic of the [[United States Intelligence Community]] and the [[Israel lobby in the United States]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.publiceye.org/rightwoo/rwooz9-09.html |title=Populist Party/Liberty Lobby Recruitment of Anti-CIA Critics |last=Berlet |first=Chip |publisher=Political Research Associates |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66tmHhIrj?url=http://www.publiceye.org/rightwoo/rwooz9-09.html |archivedate=2012-04-13 |deadurl=no |accessdate=2012-04-13 |df= }}</ref>
==Early life and background== Marchetti was born in [[Hazleton, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{Cite journal| volume = 21| issue = 1| pages = 12| last = Warner| first = John S.| title = The Marchetti Case; New Case Law| url= https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP80S01268A000200020024-4.pdf| journal = Studies in Intelligence| date = 1977}} </ref> From 1951 to 1953, he served as a corporal in U.S. Army Intelligence in France and Germany.{{sfn|Warner|1977|p=1}} Returning to the U.S. after his military service, he enrolled in [[Pennsylvania State University]], where he majored in Russian area studies, graduating with a bachelor's degree in history in 1955.{{sfn|Warner|1977|p=1}}
==Career in the Central Intelligence Agency== After a few months working as an analyst at the National Security Agency, Marchetti joined the CIA in October 1955.{{sfn|Warner|1977|p=1}} He began his career as an analyst in the Office of Research and Reports, eventually serving a tour of duty in the Office of National Estimates (ONE).{{sfn|Warner|1977|p=2}}
From ONE, Marchetti moved to the Office of Planning, Programming, and Budgeting in 1966, where he worked for over two years.{{sfn|Warner|1977|p=2}} Beginning in July 1968, he served for nine months as special assistant to [[Deputy Director of the Central Intelligence Agency|CIA Deputy Director]] [[Rufus Taylor]].{{sfn|Warner|1977|p=2}} His final position in the Agency was on the Planning, Programming, and Budget Staff of the [[National Photographic Interpretation Center]].{{sfn|Warner|1977|p=2}} Among other projects with which he was involved, Marchetti worked on setting up the [[Pine Gap]] [[satellite ground station]] near [[Alice Springs]] in Central [[Australia]].<ref>Pilger, John, ''A Secret Country'', Vintage Books, London, 1992, {{ISBN|9780099152316}}, pp. 185, 197-98, 210, 216, 225, 353, 362.</ref>
In September 1969, Marchetti resigned from the CIA.{{sfn|Warner|1977|p=2}}
==Writing career== After leaving the CIA, Marchetti began a writing career. His first work was a novel called ''The Rope-Dancer,'' published in 1971. The plot involves an officer in the "National Intelligence Agency" who becomes a spy for the Soviet Union.<ref>{{Cite journal| issn = 0028-7504| last = Barnet| first = Richard J.| title = The CIA's New Cover| accessdate = 2018-11-26| date = 1971-12-30| url = http://www.nybooks.com/articles/1971/12/30/the-cias-new-cover/}}</ref> During public appearances promoting his novel, Marchetti announced that he was writing a non-fiction work on the agency, and in March 1972 he completed a draft of an article for Esquire magazine which according to a later CIA account, included "names of agents, relations with named governments, and identifying details of ongoing operations."{{sfn|Warner|1977|p=2}} CIA received a copy of the article and an outline of Marchetti's book which he had submitted to a publisher, and decided to seek an injunction against publication.{{sfn|Warner|1977|p=2}}
On December 12, 1972, the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] denied Marchetti's appeal challenging a CIA policy that former employees must submit materials to the Agency for approval prior to publication. <ref name="Chicago Tribune; December 12, 1972">{{cite news |date=December 12, 1972 |title=Author to Defy Court on Book Ban |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1972/12/12/page/27/article/author-to-defy-court-on-book-ban |work=Chicago Tribune |volume=125 |issue=347 |edition=Final |publisher=Chicago Tribune Company |at=Section 1A, page 7 |access-date=July 31, 2017 }}</ref> Marchetti said he planned to continue with his book.<ref name="Chicago Tribune; December 12, 1972"/>
In 1974, Marchetti's book was published as ''[[The CIA and the Cult of Intelligence]]''.<ref>{{cite book |title=[[The CIA and the Cult of Intelligence]] |last1=Marchetti |first1=Victor |last2=Marks |first2=John D. |authorlink2=John D. Marks |year=1974 |publisher=Knopf |location=New York |isbn=978-0-394-48239-2}}</ref> The book, co-written with [[John D. Marks]], was harshly critical of the CIA. Before publication, the CIA demanded that Marchetti remove 399 passages, but Marchetti resisted and only 168 passages were [[censorship|censored]].<ref> Marchetti, Victor and John D. Marks. 1974. [http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/342587.The_CIA_And_The_Cult_Of_Intelligence "The CIA and the Cult of Intelligence."] New York, NY: Dell Publishing Co., Inc.</ref>{{Primary source-inline|date=September 2014}} It is the first book the federal government of the United States ever went to court to censor before its publication. The publisher ([[Alfred A. Knopf]]) chose to publish the book with blanks for censored passages and with boldface type for passages that were challenged but later uncensored.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}
In 1976 Marchetti published ''Foreign and Military Intelligence''{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} and in 1978 he published an article about the [[JFK assassination]] in the [[far-right]] newspaper of the [[Liberty Lobby]], ''[[The Spotlight]].'' Marchetti, a proponent of the [[John F. Kennedy assassination conspiracy theories#Organized crime conspiracy|organized crime and the CIA conspiracy]] theory, claimed that the [[House Select Committee on Assassinations]] revealed a CIA memo from 1966 that named [[E. Howard Hunt]], [[Frank Sturgis]] and [[Gerry Patrick Hemming]] in the JFK assassination. Marchetti also claimed that [[Marita Lorenz]] offered sworn testimony to confirm this. The HSCA reported that it had not received such a memo and rejected theories that Hunt was involved in a plot to kill Kennedy.<ref name="Miami Herald; February 2, 1985">{{cite news |last=Doig |first=Stephen K. |date=February 2, 1985 |title=Ex-CIA agent admits he used JFK 'rumors' |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP91-00587R000100610022-2.pdf |work=Miami Herald |location=Miami |page=2B |access-date=April 9, 2017}}</ref>
In 1981, [[E. Howard Hunt]] sued the Liberty Lobby and Marchetti for [[defamation]] and won $650,000 in damages. Liberty Lobby appealed the case with lawyer, [[Mark Lane (author)|Mark Lane]]. On February 1, 1985, Marchetti stated that key parts of his of articles were based upon rumors that he heard from ''[[Penthouse (magazine)|Penthouse]]'' columnist Bill Corson and that he had no corroboration of Corson's story.<ref name="Miami Herald; February 2, 1985"/> Corson had provided an earlier deposition stating that he not discussed the rumors with Marchetti.<ref name="Miami Herald; February 2, 1985"/> Marchetti, Liberty Lobby and Lane won the appeal in 1985.<ref name="Miami Herald; February 7, 1985">{{cite news |last=Doig |first=Stephen K. |date=February 7, 1985 |title=Hunt-JFK article 'trash' but not libelous, jury finds |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP90-00806R000100650001-8.pdf |work=Miami Herald |location=Miami |page=1A |access-date=April 9, 2017}}</ref> Commenting afterward, two jurors rejected that the conspiracy theories offered by Lane influenced the verdict.<ref name="Miami Herald; February 7, 1985"/> Lane wrote a book, ''[[Plausible Denial]]'', to describe the unfolding of that historic trial.
==Death== Marchetti suffered from dementia in his last years. He died at his home in [[Ashburn, Virginia]] at the age of 88.<ref>Schudel, 2018</ref>
